Anonymous Mon 15 Jun 2020 02:31:31 No.30913865 Report
Quoted By: >>30913903
So! "Where Kitsune Wait" was a darn good read and I am really looking forward to more.

As a period piece, the language used in dialogue and in the Egil's internal thought processes is great. I think you did a much better job than I did with "The Knight's Ward", which was somewhere around 13-15th century European-analogue nation. Yours I'm guessing (literally just guessing, my knowledge on the subject is almost non-existent) is early teens century Japan? Whereas I felt comfortable falling back to a more casual style of conversation and even relied on some phrasing or dialogue that felt a little too modern for the story, your story reads like it sticks very rigidly to its era. My ONLY complaint about it is the use of titles, specifically whenever there is interaction between the sisters, there's just an absolute ton of "dear sister, elder sister, younger sister". I don't know how titles worked in this era but when reading I became very cognizant of how many times I was reading these titles over and over.

On the topic of over-used words: ORBS. ORBS EVERYWHERE. You use orbs in place of eyes an absolute ton.

Characterization is fantastic. Despite the plethora of named characters I feel like I have a pretty good understanding of most of them, if not all. It takes a lot of skill to be able to keep characters discernable when you have no many in the story, let alone so many interacting in a single scene. It is a skill I lack, so when I see it I'm always kind of jealous.

The story could use an editing pass for errors. Nobody is perfect, but here and there you'll sometimes have a word outright missing, or quotes will be missing from spoken dialogue.

Pacing is good. We are immediately introduced by Egil to what will obviously become an important story element later on, but that is placed briefly on the backburner as the story shifts to his developing relationship with the sisters. Then the early lead is developed and we have our main problem and the quest to solve it, and it seems we are getting rather close to a serious confrontation, if not the main one depending on how long you plan for this to be. There's not much in the way of meandering about the story. I didn't feel as if I was being led down a side-path just to make main the main one feel like it would take longer. Getting from plot-point to plot-point appears satisfyingly snappy without seeming rushed. The only time I felt as if I was looking to "get on with it" was whenever Egil and one of the sisters would round-about about who doesn't need to apologize to who. While more an element of characterization, I felt like these exchanges ground the dialogue to an unceremonious halt, which I felt interfered slightly with pacing.

I just really like the story. I was bored at work and started it during some downtime, and then as I got further and further my breaks got a little longer, my bathroom breaks got a little longer, all so I could keep trying to read more and more. Eventually finished it before my shift was over. I really look forward to more, Somethingaboutsharks.
